description:
&lt;p&gt;We are looking for an experienced and highly motivated Clinical or Counselling Psychologist to join us for a fixed term contract for 2 days a week for 4-6 months (depending on start date). This is an exciting opportunity to co-lead psychological provision for the Psychiatric Intensive Care Units (PICU) in the Tower Hamlets Centre for Mental Health. The PICU wards consist of a female ward (Rosebank) which has 13 beds, and a male ward (Millharbour), which has 11 beds.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You will work closely with the other PICU Psychologists, and the Operational and Clinical Leads to ensure the delivery of a high quality psychological service to service users and families. You will promote psychologically informed practice throughout PICU through reflective practice and consultation (formal and informal) with the staff team, and will contribute to staff training with senior colleagues. There are significant opportunities for service development, particularly around the implementation of trauma informed care on Rosebank.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We are looking for someone who is keen to take on the challenges of working in a diverse borough with very complex and acutely distressed patients in an inpatient setting. The post holder will need to have an interest and experience of working with severe and enduring mental illness and high comorbidity with clients from a range of religious, cultural and ethnic backgrounds. We are seeking someone who values and enjoys multi-disciplinary team working, indirect psychological interventions, and collaborating therapeutically with Arts and Occupational Therapies. We welcome innovations and a readiness to try out new ideas as part of our commitment to continuous improvement and the development of our staff.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Your service area is part of the wider psychology and psychological therapy provision in Tower Hamlets, and you would be joining a community of inpatient psychologists, as well as psychologists and psychological colleagues working in CMHT, EI, perinatal, art therapies, personalities disorder services, homelessness, learning difficulties, older adults, PTS, psychiatric liaison, community health, community access service and primary care settings. The department aims to develop and deliver our services through coproduction with people with lived experience and has an excellent relationship with the Local Recovery College. We meet regularly and support professional development in a range of ways.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
